  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="TK10">
<l>piṟavip peruṅkaṭa ṉīntuvar nīntā</l>
<l>riṟaiva ṉaṭicērā tār</l>            
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>They will cross the great ocean of birth. They do not cross</l>
<l>without first coming to the feet of the Lord.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>
  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <head>Parimēlaḻakar</head>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK10_P1">
          (i-ḷ). iṟaiva ṉaṭiyeṉṉum puṇaiyaic cērntār piṟaviyākiya periyakaṭalai nīntuvar, ataṉaic cērātar nīntamāṭṭārāy ataṉu ḷaḻuntuvar, (e-ṟu).
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          The meaning ... : Those who have united with the boat called/known as the feet of the Lord will swim the great ocean that is birth; those who do not unite with them, being unable to swim, will drown in it.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK10_P2">
          kāraṇa kāriyat toṭarcciyāyk karaiyiṉri varutaliṉ ‘piṟavip peruṅkaṭal’ eṉṟār. cērntā reṉpatu colleccam. ulakiyalpai niṉaiyātu iṟaivaṉaṭiyaiyē niṉaippārkkup piṟaviyaṟutalum avvāṟaṉṟi māṟi niṉaippārk kaḵtaṟāmaiyum ākiya iraṇṭum itaṉāl niyamikkappaṭṭaṉa.
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          Because [rebirth], being(?) a constant succession of cause and effect, [keeps] coming without limit (lit. "shore"), [the poet] has said, "the great ocean of birth." "Those who have united" is a word to be supplied. Both [ideas?]—namely that [re]birth is cut off for those who, without thinking of worldly natures(?), think only of the feet of the Lord; and that for those who do not think that way, conversely(?), it is not cut off—have been determined by this [verse].
        </p>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <head>Maṇakkuṭavar (9)</head>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="TK10_M">
          <l>piṟavip peruṅkaṭal nīntuvar nīntā</l>
          <l>riṟaivaṉaṭi cērā tavar.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>They will swim the great ocean of birth. They cannot swim</l>
          <l>without first coming to the feet of the Lord.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK10_M1">
          (i - ḷ.) piṟaviyākiya periyakaṭalai nīnti yēṟuvar iṟaivaṉatu aṭiyaic cērntavar; cērātavar ataṉuḷ aḻuntuvar.
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          They who have swum across the great ocean that is birth are they who have united with the feet of the Lord; they who do not unite [with them] will drown in it.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK10_M2">
          itu, piṟavi illai yeṉṟatu.
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          This [amounts to saying] that there is no [re]birth [for them].
        </p>
      </div>
    </body>
